title: CUDA / TensorRT - Exception during initialization: std::bad_alloc
body:
**Describe the bug**
Running onnxruntime w/ TensorRT built from source (master branch at the time of this post). 

My model runs fine on the CPU but when I try to move it to the GPU I get the following error while it is loading the model:

```
2021-02-12 22:13:52.008378106 [E:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:1290 operator()] Exception during initialization: std::bad_alloc
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'Ort::Exception'
  what():  Exception during initialization: std::bad_alloc
```

The only change I made was to add the relevant headers and add these few lines to start using TensorRT:

```
    // GPU Settings
    int device_id = 0;

    // Integrate CUDA / TensorRT
    Ort::ThrowOnError(OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_Tensorrt(session_options, device_id));
    Ort::ThrowOnError(OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(session_options, device_id));
```

The GPU memory gets to about 240MB of usage before the bad_alloc error happens. I am running a 2070 Super w/ 8GB GPU Memory.

The code I am using is a modified version of this sample, the only changes being to load my model (changing input & output sizes): https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/csharp/test/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.EndToEndTests.Capi/CXX_Api_Sample.cpp 

The Dockerfile I used to build the environment was, again modified to build the C++ shared libraries instead of the python wheel: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.tensorrt


UPDATE - After running the model through `symbolic_shape_infer.py` with `--auto-merge` I now get a different error:

```
2021-02-15 16:36:42.992440323 [E:onnxruntime:test, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:47 log] [2021-02-15 16:36:42   ERROR] [TRT]/code/onnxruntime/cmake/external/onnx-tensorrt/onnx2trt_utils.cpp:467: Found unsupported datatype (11) when importing initializer: 1307
```

title: Lifetime of the strings inside OrtOpenVINOProviderOptions

labels.name: ep:OpenVINO
labels.description: issues related to OpenVINO execution provider

body:
The new `OrtOpenVINOProviderOptions` struct has a couple of strings inside it, `device_id` and `device_type`. What's the expected lifetime of those strings? Similarly how long does the struct itself need to live? Is there a reference held to it after the `ORT_API2_STATUS(SessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO, _In_ OrtSessionOptions* options, _In_ const OrtOpenVINOProviderOptions* provider_options)` call returns?

My reading of the C++ code underlying the create call is that the pointers are copied rather than the memory they point to, meaning the char arrays need to outlive the provider, in which case I'll need to add some tracking code to the Java API to free them whenever anyone adds an OpenVINO provider (which will be a pain). In python it looks like it pulls out the C string, but I don't know if Python pins memory to make that ok.

In general is there any guidance on the lifetime of memory passed into provider factories? The CUDA and TensorRT ones seem to accept function pointers, so that seems less of an issue.

title: Rename Python packaging pipelines
Rebase ortmodule-api branch on master
body:
The point of this PR is to validate builds. Once that is done we will need to force push this branch on thiagofc/ortmodule-api to rewrite the history.

For the ease of reviewing, apart from rebasing I made the below changes to make builds pass on master (please note in the dev branch we DO NOT run all the CIs that run in master, hence there were bugs checked-in that broke the build):
	
 - Moved event_pool, message_queue and bias dropout fusion to core from training, since they are used in inference code where training headers are not accessible and CIs on master will fail at compilation stage.
 
 - Reduced binary size to make Minimal build CI pass, here I basically wrapped background thread related code in TRAINING ifdef since it was written in inference_session.cc which is a common file for inference and training.
 
 - A recent pytorch nightly build broke ORTModule because they got rid of container_abcs, I changed ORTModule to import it from collections.abc
 
 - Also validated ORTModule runs expected batch size with expected throughput on NV-BERT-Large.
 
 - History looks clean now!  Its easy to see what this feature contains and all the fluff from master is gone.

title: MLAS: add uint8_t NHWC max pooling
body:
**Description**: Add support to transform graphs containing uint8 MaxPool to a custom operator that supports NHWC format that can be more easily vectorized.

**Motivation and Context**
Add support to:
1. Extend the NCHW->NHWC graph transformer to recognized MaxPool(uint8) and replace this with com.ms.NhwcMaxPool(uint8).
2. Implement the com.ms.NhwcMaxPool operator.
3. Implement a MLAS routine to do a vectorized MaxPool using an indirection buffer.

Although the current implementation of NhwcMaxPool is single threaded, this easily beats the old code path of transposing back to NCHW, running a scalar MaxPool, then typically transposing back to NHWC for additional convolutions.

title: ONNX runtime session can't load model with external data outside of current folder.
body:

**Urgency**
Many large models like BART, DLRM require external data because models are bigger than 2GB.

**System information**

mkdir t

#run Python script:

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):

        self.fc = nn.Linear(1024, 1024 * 1024)
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.fc(x)
        return x
model = Net()
input = torch.randn(1024, requires_grad=True)
with torch.no_grad():
    torch.onnx.export(model, (input, ), './t/net.onnx', do_constant_folding=True, opset_version=12,  use_external_data_format=True, enable_onnx_checker=True)
import onnx
import onnxruntime
m = onnx.load("./t/net.onnx", load_external_data=False)

onnxruntime.InferenceSession(model_payload)

title: Support for 3D ConvTranspose in CUDA execution provider

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
For a 3D U-Net model containing a ConvTranspose, the inference fails when using the CUDA execution provider, returning the following error:

> Non-zero status code returned while running ConvTranspose node. Name:'PartitionedCall/PartitionedCall/model_2/model_1/conv3d_transpose/conv3d_transpose' Status Message: Input X must be 3- or 4-dimensional. X: {1,256,16,7,7}

Using the CPU execution provider everything works fine.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 1.6.0

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I would like to request support for ConvTranspose with more than two spatial dimensions in the CUDA execution provider.
While 3D would be enough for my use-case, the [ConvTranspose operator](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#ConvTranspose) is supposed to work for an arbitrary number of dimensions (N x C x D1 x D2 ... x Dn).

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
None considered.

**Additional context**
This is very much the same issue as #965, but this time for the CUDA execution provider.

The error is raised at the following location in the code, which is also accommodated by a TODO regarding this problem:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/33279250b57764bd65487ea91a4f92d576e03c20/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/nn/conv_transpose.cc#L51

title: TensorRT EP API for environment variables (esp, on FP16, INT8)

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
For various environment variables on TensorRT EP, ONNXRT needs to provide an API to override settings per model based.
The most critical environment variables are FP16 (ORT_TENSORRT_FP16_ENABLE) and INT8 (ORT_TENSORRT_INT8_ENABLE) for performance.
 
This will provide scalability and generality, for example, on Triton Inference server. TensorFlow has an API for FP16 support. 
This issue was originated from Huggingface when they run Triton experiments on ONNXRT, TensorFlow, TensorRT backends.
(See https://github.com/triton-inference-server/onnxruntime_backend/issues/20#issuecomment-778686795: Triton-ONNXRT model’s config needs to be able to enable FP16 inferencing (like Triton-TensorFlow) as a 1st priority so that there is no server downtime without restarting with docker run -e ORT_TENSORRT_FP16_ENABLE=1)

title: [WinML] Threadpool consumes all available CPU during real-time CPU inference

labels.name: platform:windows
labels.description: issues related to the Windows platform

body:
**Describe the bug**
Hey,

I'm working with WinML, using the C++/WinRT runtime (Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning package) for **real-time** inferencing. GPU inference is Ok. But on CPU, the runtime threadpool consumes all available CPU cycles (EigenNonBlockingThreadPool.h, body of the WorkerLoop function). It brings the global load to close to 100%, even with small computational needs. It is problematic in terms of power consumption and usability. The CPU will run at its max power even with lightweight DNNs, and it makes it impossible to secure the real-time inference process by adjusting process priority, as such will jeopardize the system's reactivity and stability.
Other builds of the runtime use OpenMP's threadpool instead. By default, they have the same problem, but the active/passive policy can be changed with the OWP_WAIT_POLICY environment variable, which fixes everything.

**Urgency**
Moderate - we do have deadlines, but we are investigating alternatives, such as using other runtime builds. However using the C++/WinRT build is not only the recommended thing to do, it is also the most convenient and reliable.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10 20H2
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0
- Python version: N/A
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2017 (15.9.33)
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A
- CUDA/cuDNN version: N/A
- GPU model and memory: N/A

**To Reproduce**
Run real-time inference on a model using the CPU LearningModelDevice category - that is, periodic model evaluations of small data batches. The global CPU load will rise to 100% even when the DNN model used is lightweight.

**Expected behavior**
The CPU load with CPU inference should match the computational load induced by inferencing. Or there should be some way to configure the threadpool policy, as with OpenMP.

**Screenshots**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/64973054/108187895-3f935380-710f-11eb-8d44-05fae3e0a8e1.png)
Performance profiling of real-time inference using a relatively small model.

**Additional context**
N/A

title: INT8 quantized model is very slow
body:
Hello,

I used onnxruntime's quantize_dynamic() and qunatize_static() to get the INT8 quantized versions of my original model, which is a flavor of SSD model. Accuracy of the quantized models is acceptable.

But when I run the benchmark tool (i.e) [onnxruntime_test.py](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/onnxruntime_test.py) on these models, I find that the quantized models are very slow both on CPU and GPU:

Model | CPU Latency (ms) | GPU Latency (ms)

Original | 5.42 | 3.41
INT8 - Dynamic  | 45.76 | 27.66
INT8 – Static  | 17.32 | 9.3

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution Centos 7
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary 
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0
- Python version: 3.6
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.2/8
- GPU model and memory: V100/32GB
- ONNX version: 1.8.1

**To Reproduce**
I attach the 3 ONNX models here. 
[ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.int8.QD.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5998148/ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.int8.QD.onnx.zip)
[ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.int8.QS_1.6.0.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5998150/ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.int8.QS_1.6.0.onnx.zip)
[ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5998151/ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.onnx.zip)

One can generate the dynamically quantized model ('QD') by using onnxruntime.quantize_dynamic() on the original model as follows:


import onnx
from onnxruntime.quantization import quantize_dynamic, QuantType

model_fp32 = "ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.onnx"
model_quant = "ssd300_ft_pruned_0.75.8.int8.QD.onnx
quantized_model = quantize_dynamic(model_fp32, model_quant, weight_type=QuantType.QUInt8)


I will share the static quantization code later if needed.

**Expected behavior**
From what I learnt, INT8 models are supposed to run faster than their FP32 counterparts and I have verified this independently on Openvino platform. However, this is not happening in this particular case with onnxruntime.

title: Make it easier to fold MakeString usages to reduce binary size.
body:
**Description**: 
MakeString is often used with string literals, which have a type of char[n]. As the 'n' differs based on the length of the string literal it makes it harder to re-use the combinations of types in the MakeString template instantiation.

Add a layer to decay a char[n] argument to char* so that we can re-use the MakeString implementation for a combination of types more effectively.

Tested with various platforms and build types to validate. All tests showed a reduction in size. Example reductions for two main build types:

Android MinSizeRel minimal build, static libc++, no ops, no exceptions (i.e. ORT mobile base build)
 - Before: 1,129,344
 - After: 1,096,576
 - Saving: 32KB

Windows Release build with all ops
  - Before: 7,244,800
  - After: 7,193,088
 - Saving: 50KB


**Motivation and Context**
Reduce binary size from MakeString

title: Quantizer does not correctly set QType in quantized_value_map for int8 input
body:
**Describe the bug**
In the quantizer, the `QuantizedValue` is constructed like

```
QuantizedValue(node.output[0], node.output[0] + "_quantized",
                                                quantized_input_value.scale_name, quantized_input_value.zp_name,
                                                QuantizedValueType.Input)
```

in most of the operators. However, this sets the `qType` to the default value of `uint8`, which may not actually match the quantized data type (if e.g. we set inputs to be quantized as `int8`). While this works fine if the inputs are going to be quantized to `uint8`, if the inputs are quantized to `int8` then this causes an obvious issue.

Even though I noticed that the quantizer does not officially support `int8` yet, this is a straightforward fix that will not break anything else; and with this change added, `int8` models can be quantized properly.

I submitted a PR for this a month or so back https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/6179/ but it seems to be stuck in review-limbo.

**Urgency**
Not urgent, but having this merged in would remove some of the discrepancy between our fork and upstream.

title: Fix longformer parity and perf regression
body:

(2) Update convert_longformer_to_onnx: support  transformers 4.3.2, where an extra parameter is added to LongformerSelfAttention.forward; add an option --export_padding so that user could choose whether to have padding logic in ONNX model.
(3) Improve benchmark_longformer tool: add memory measurement

To use new kernel, set environment variable ORT_LONGFORMER_COMPACT_MEMORY=1. Note that when sequence_length <= 2 * attention_window or global_tokens > attention_window, we will use old kernel and ignore the environment variable. This is for experimental purpose, and the environment variable might be removed in the future.

**Motivation and Context**

Walk around a few issues in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/6646:

(2) There is additional constraint that number of global tokens <= attention_window.
